{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20900"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20900"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13775"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79448"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12470"},{"type":"tags","id":"12723"},{"type":"tags","id":"12724"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33206"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA laboratory test is used to detect antibodies in a patient\u0027s blood sample. The test involves mixing the patient\u0027s serum with a known antigen in a gel medium. A positive result is indicated by the formation of visible antigen-antibody complexes. This test has limited applications due to its requirement for large quantities of antibody or antigen to produce visible results. It is sometimes used in the diagnosis of fungal infections and pyogenic meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory techniques is being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Agglutination test","Complement fixation test","Precipitation test","Enzyme immunoassay","Western blot test"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description refers to a \u003Cstrong\u003Eprecipitation test\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterized by the formation of visible antigen-antibody complexes in a gel medium or solution. These tests measure antigens or antibodies in body fluids based on the degree of visible precipitation that forms when antigen-antibody complexes develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAgglutination test\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves the clumping of particles (such as red blood cells or latex beads) coated with antigens when mixed with specific antibodies, rather than precipitation in a gel.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement fixation test\u003C/strong\u003E - This measures the reduction of complement activity following an antigen-antibody reaction, using an indicator system to detect remaining complement.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnzyme immunoassay\u003C/strong\u003E - This technique uses enzymes linked to antibodies or antigens to generate a measurable signal, typically a color change, and does not rely on visible precipitation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWestern blot test\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves separating proteins by gel electrophoresis, transferring them to a membrane, and then detecting specific proteins using labeled antibodies.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrecipitation tests have limited applications in modern clinical laboratories due to their low sensitivity, as they require large amounts of antibody or antigen to produce visible results. They are sometimes used in the diagnosis of fungal infections and pyogenic meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Precipitation tests detect antigens or antibodies by forming visible antigen-antibody complexes in gel or solution.","Precipitation tests have low sensitivity as they require large amounts of antibody or antigen to produce visible results.","Precipitation tests are used to detect antibodies in suspected fungal infections or pyogenic meningitis."],"references":["Vazquez-Pertejo MT, Bush LM. Immunologic Tests for Infectious Disease. Merck Manual Professional Edition. January 2025. Available from: https://www.merckmanuals.com/professional/infectious-diseases/laboratory-diagnosis-of-infectious-disease/immunologic-tests-for-infectious-disease"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79448"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20900"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79448"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:53:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T17:09:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13775"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96833"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCou